        "description": "This project provides multiple Arduino timer options with on/off setpoints that can be programmed with hours, minutes, and seconds, and settings are saved on the EEPROM. Options include a timer for everyday, a timer with selectable day, and a setup with 4 timers for a single relay. The timers can recover data even after power failure. The project uses a compact design with 3 buttons and a 16x2 LCD for easy use.",
        "steps": [
            "Set up the LCD by connecting VCC to Arduino 5V, GND to Arduino GND, SDA to Arduino analog pin 4, and SCL to Arduino analog pin 5. Upload the 'I2C scanner' code to find your LCD address and replace the default address (0x3F) if needed.",
            "Program the RTC 3231 module by adding the RTClib library to Arduino, uploading the ds3231 example code, and ensuring the computer's date and time are correct during compilation and upload. Connect the RTC module to Arduino using the same SDA and SCL pins as the LCD.",
            "Clear the Arduino's EEPROM by uploading the eeprom_clear code from the EEPROM examples. This sets all EEPROM values to 0, ensuring a clean state for timer settings. Wait for the pin 13 LED to turn on to confirm completion.",
            "Implement the timer logic by converting the current time and on/off setpoints into single numbers for easier comparison. Use byte data types for storing the values of hours, minutes, and seconds. Use unsigned long to convert for single numbers.",
            "Compare the current time with the on/off setpoints to control the relay. Implement logic to handle scenarios where the on time is before or after the off time, ensuring the relay activates correctly even with power interruptions.",
            "Build an interface using buttons to change the on/off settings. This allows you to store the new settings onto the EEPROM for persistent configuration. Use three buttons for moving between pages and selecting options in submenus.",
            "Assemble the circuit by connecting the LCD, RTC, buttons, resistors, and relay module to the Arduino Uno board using a breadboard and wires.",
            "Upload the appropriate code for the desired timer configuration (everyday, selectable day, or 4 timers) to the Arduino board. Ensure that the required libraries (RTClib and LiquidCrystal_I2C) are included."
